    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:79805be2-571c-4408-be3d-d2df6608326f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 15-year-old girl who arrives looking tired, guarded, and older than her age in the way prolonged sadness can make an adolescent seem. She is dressed appropriately but with little attention to style, wearing an oversized sweatshirt and keeping her sleeves pulled over her hands. Her posture is slouched, eye contact is intermittent, and her speech is soft with delayed responses. She reports feeling \"empty\" and \"numb\" most days, with occasional tearfulness when discussing school, friendships, and her sense that she is disappointing everyone around her.\n\nOver the last two months, {patientName} has withdrawn from activities she used to enjoy, especially drawing, listening to music with friends, and playing junior varsity soccer. She still attends school but has had falling grades, trouble concentrating in class, and frequent absences related to fatigue and poor sleep. She spends much of her time alone in her room after school scrolling on her phone without much interest, often staying awake late and struggling to get up in the morning. Her appetite has been reduced, and she has unintentionally lost a small amount of weight.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her mother, younger brother, and her mother's partner. Family relationships are strained but caring; her mother is worried and has noticed irritability, isolation, and a loss of motivation. {patientName} has one close friend she still texts occasionally, though she has recently turned down invitations to hang out. She denies alcohol or drug use and is not sexually active. She enjoys sketching fantasy characters and used to post her art online, but she has largely stopped because she feels it is \"not good enough anymore.\"\n\nIn conversation, {patientName} describes persistent low mood, loss of pleasure, poor energy, insomnia, feelings of worthlessness, and difficulty concentrating. She endorses passive thoughts that it would be easier not to wake up but denies a current plan or intent to harm herself. She is frightened by these thoughts and relieved when asked directly about them. She wants help but is unsure treatment will make a difference, reflecting the hopelessness often present in depressive episodes during adolescence."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4e519051-d01a-4340-a989-04bf73cbf29e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
